<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Why these words?</div>
  <p>This unit asks you to take a stakeholder perspective in a water-rights case and write a Position Paper defending that perspective. You will work with cases like the Cauvery dispute. The vocabulary below gives you the precise terms used by hydrologists, lawyers, and policy advocates.</p>
</div>

<h2>Vocabulary</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>What it means + visual cue</th>
      <th>Sentence stem</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Watershed</strong></td>
      <td>The area of land where all water drains to a single river or sea. Crosses political boundaries; creates conflict. <em>Visual: Bowl-shaped terrain with arrows converging to a central river.</em></td>
      <td>This case takes place in the ___ watershed.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Aquifer</strong></td>
      <td>An underground layer of porous rock that stores groundwater. Recharged slowly; can be over-pumped. <em>Visual: Cross-section: water-filled porous rock beneath the surface.</em></td>
      <td>The ___ aquifer is being depleted at a rate of ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Riparian</strong></td>
      <td>Relating to land along the bank of a river. Riparian rights = legal rights to water based on owning land along it. <em>Visual: Strip of green vegetation along a riverbank.</em></td>
      <td>Riparian rights in this case mean ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Water rights</strong></td>
      <td>Legal entitlements to use a specific quantity of water from a source. Vary by country and history — often centuries old. <em>Visual: Legal document with a water droplet seal.</em></td>
      <td>Water rights in this case are based on ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Allocation</strong></td>
      <td>How water from a shared source is divided among users. Often the heart of the conflict. <em>Visual: Pie chart of water divided among users.</em></td>
      <td>Current allocation gives ___ to ___ and ___ to ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Stakeholder</strong></td>
      <td>Any person, group, or system with an interest in or affected by the water decision. Includes humans AND ecosystems. <em>Visual: Multiple figures around a table, with a river behind them.</em></td>
      <td>The stakeholder I am representing is ___, whose interests are ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Upstream / downstream</strong></td>
      <td>Upstream = closer to the river's source; downstream = closer to its mouth. Upstream users affect downstream users. <em>Visual: Arrow flowing from mountains to ocean with users at both ends.</em></td>
      <td>As an upstream / downstream user, my client experiences ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Consumptive use</strong></td>
      <td>Water use that removes water from the system permanently (evaporation, crop uptake). Different from non-consumptive use (hydropower, recreation). <em>Visual: Plant absorbing water vs. waterwheel returning water to the stream.</em></td>
      <td>This use is consumptive / non-consumptive because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Drought</strong></td>
      <td>A prolonged period of below-average precipitation. Triggers competition and conflict over allocation. <em>Visual: Cracked dry ground.</em></td>
      <td>During drought conditions in ___, ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Flood</strong></td>
      <td>Excess water overflowing onto normally dry land. Different from drought but often affects the same stakeholders. <em>Visual: Water spilling over a riverbank into a town.</em></td>
      <td>Flood risk in this case affects ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Transboundary</strong></td>
      <td>Crossing political boundaries — between states (Cauvery), countries (Nile, Mekong), or jurisdictions. <em>Visual: River crossing dashed political border lines.</em></td>
      <td>This is a transboundary water issue because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Treaty / agreement</strong></td>
      <td>A formal arrangement between parties to govern water sharing. Some hold; some fail under stress. <em>Visual: Two flags shaking hands above a river.</em></td>
      <td>The relevant treaty / agreement here is ___, which says ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Equity</strong></td>
      <td>Fairness in how water is shared. Different from equality — may mean giving more to those with greater historical disadvantage. <em>Visual: Three people of different sizes drinking from differently-sized cups.</em></td>
      <td>An equity issue in this allocation is ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Ecosystem flow</strong></td>
      <td>The amount of water that must remain in a river to keep its ecosystem (fish, wetlands, deltas) functioning. <em>Visual: Fish swimming in a river with a minimum-flow line marked.</em></td>
      <td>Ecosystem flow requirements at this site are ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Position</strong></td>
      <td>Your defended stance in the position paper — what you are arguing should happen, on whose behalf, with what evidence. <em>Visual: Person standing firmly behind a labeled flag.</em></td>
      <td>My position is that ___, on behalf of ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Counter-argument</strong></td>
      <td>The strongest objection to your position. A good position paper addresses it head-on rather than ignoring it. <em>Visual: Two arrows colliding head-on.</em></td>
      <td>The strongest counter to my position is ___. I respond by ___.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">🛠️ In-class pre-teach activity (10 min)</div>
  <p><strong>Stakeholder swap.</strong> I will assign you a stakeholder role for a brief case (not one you will be using for the assessment). In 5 minutes, write 3 sentences from that stakeholder's perspective using at least 5 terms from this list. Then swap with a partner and critique each other.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">💬 Paired discussion prompt</div>
  <p>With a partner: each of you pick a stakeholder from the same case. Argue your position for 90 seconds each. Then together, write one sentence that fairly summarizes BOTH positions without favoring either.</p>
</div>

